ce:section.ce:para:
The rapid and sensitive detection of organic solvents is critical for environmental protection as well as human health and safety [55]. On this basis, the fluorescence sensing properties of complex 1 to various common organic molecules were studied. When complex 1 is exposed to NB, its fluorescence is entirely suppressed compared to other solvents (Fig. 6
                           a), implying that complex 1 may be employed as an excellent fluorescence sensor for the detection of NB in solution. Titration studies were performed to further investigate quantitative detection capabilities of complex 1 for NB, and it was discovered that the emission intensity of complex 1 reduced as the NB concentration increased. Fig. 6b shows the linear relationship between the complex 1 and NB. The KSV curve of NB has a good linear relationship at low concentration with the value of 0.01 M−1 as well as the LOD is 12.87 μM for NB. (Fig. 6c) The results demonstrate that complex 1 is a good NB sensor. The 5-day fluorescence test still had a satisfactory quenching effect on complex 1 for detecting NB, as shown in Fig. S5. Furthermore, when compared to existing CP-based sensors (Table 4
                           ), complex 1 has a reduced LOD and so performs better than previously reported compounds for NB sensing.

A series of experiments show that complex 1 has good fluorescence quenching effect on four metal ions (Fe3+, Cu2+, Co2+, Ni2+), one anion (Cr2O7
                        2−) and one organic solvent (NB). More studies are being carried out to investigate the mechanism of fluorescence quenching (Figs. S6 and S7). Fluorescence quenching is primarily comprised of three processes: structural degradation, fluorescence resonance energy transfer (FRET), and ion exchange [58]. The samples soaked in 5 different ions were tested by PXRD (Fig. S6). The sample was discovered to be dissolved in NB during the experiment, proving that the fluorescence quenching effect of NB was caused by the collapse of the sample framework. On the contrast, the sample in Cr2O7
                        2− anion had some changes on the sample framework (Fig. S6). Therefore, the quenching effect of Cr2O7
                        2− anion on the sample is due to skeleton collapse. The FRET mechanism is also widely considered to be the cause of fluorescence quenching. The FRET process is ascribed to competition for available light absorption between the analyte and the complex, thus we evaluated the UV−vis spectra and emission spectra of the remaining four ions (Fe3+, Cu2+, Co2+, Ni2+) (Fig. 7
                        ). From the study of spectral overlap, the absorption spectra of analytes with different ions (Fe3+, Cu2+, Co2+, Ni2+) clearly overlapped with the emission spectra of In-phen complexes. As a result, competitive adsorption between each analyte and the In-phen complex may be clearly illustrated. Fe3+ ion displayed the greatest overlap, followed by Ni2+, Cu2+, and Co2+ ions, implying that the fluorescence quenching was caused by competition between each absorbance of analyte and the emission of the complex 1. Furthermore, the FRET process is regarded as a dependable quenching mechanism that primarily influences fluorescence quenching efficiency via the electron transfer process between the donor and acceptor. Moreover, in comparison to the other analytes, the absorption spectra of Fe3+ overlaps greatly with the emission spectrum of the complex, which may explain why complex 1 is more sensitive to Fe3+ ion (Scheme 2
                        ).
